Languages play a vital role in development, ensuring diversity and inter-cultural dialogue according to the United Nations. Education Department's spokesperson Elijah Mhlanga discussed the importance of language in schools. Courtesy of #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - It's International Mother Language Day. According to the United Nations, languages play a vital role in development, ensuring diversity and inter-cultural dialogue. The Basic Education Department says there are different initiatives in place at schools but there are still parents who don’t want their children learning an African language. READ: Mother tongues the key to preserving heritage The department's Elijah Mhlanga says a mindset change is needed. "First and foremost, it’s the availability of teachers because that's what you need it is them who is responsible for teaching the languages.... if there are no people to make sure the languages are taught you are not going to win. That's why we have even gone to use bursary program to make a condition for young people choosing teaching as a career to consider taking African languages and teach it primary schools," he said. "We have seen a gradual change over tie in the number of children who are taking African languages but we have a situation where parents don't want. We need a mindset change."